/-!
## The most fragile variant: dropping pairwise coprimality

The most fragile weakening of Erdős Problem 123 is dropping the pairwise coprimality
condition. When `a = b = c = p` for a prime `p > 1`, we have:

  `PowTripleSet p p p = {p^n : n ≥ 0}`

In this set, for any two distinct elements `p^i` and `p^j` with `i < j`,
we have `p^i ∣ p^j`. This means every division-antichain subset has at most
one element, so the only representable sums are `{0} ∪ {p^n : n ≥ 0}`.
Since not all sufficiently large naturals are powers of `p`, the set is NOT
d-complete. This shows the coprimality condition is essential.
-/

/-
PROBLEM
In a set of powers of `a` (with `a ≥ 2`), any two distinct elements
have a divisibility relation, so no antichain of size ≥ 2 exists.

PROVIDED SOLUTION
Since s has at least 2 elements, pick two distinct elements x, y ∈ s. By hsub, x = a^m, y = a^n for some m, n. Since x ≠ y, m ≠ n. WLOG m < n (use Nat.lt_or_gt_of_ne). Then a^m | a^n (by pow_dvd_pow). So IsDivisionAntichain fails.
-/
lemma powers_not_antichain {a : ℕ} (ha : 2 ≤ a) (s : Finset ℕ)
    (hsub : ∀ x ∈ s, ∃ n : ℕ, x = a ^ n)
    (hcard : 2 ≤ s.card) : ¬ IsDivisionAntichain s := by
  obtain ⟨ x, hx, y, hy, hxy ⟩ := Finset.one_lt_card.1 hcard;
  have := hsub x hx; have := hsub y hy; obtain ⟨ i, rfl ⟩ := this; obtain ⟨ j, rfl ⟩ := this; rcases le_total i j with hij | hij <;> simp_all +decide [ IsDivisionAntichain, pow_dvd_pow_iff ] ;
  · exact ⟨ a ^ i, hy, a ^ j, hx, Ne.symm hxy, pow_dvd_pow _ hij ⟩;
  · exact ⟨ _, hx, _, hy, hxy, pow_dvd_pow _ hij ⟩

/-
PROBLEM
When a = b = c, the PowTripleSet reduces to just powers.

PROVIDED SOLUTION
Show set extensionality. For the forward direction: n = a^i * a^j * a^k = a^(i+j+k), take m = i+j+k. For the reverse: n = a^m, take i=m, j=0, k=0, then a^m * a^0 * a^0 = a^m.
-/
lemma PowTripleSet_eq_self (a : ℕ) :
    PowTripleSet a a a = {n | ∃ m : ℕ, n = a ^ m} := by
  ext n
  simp;
  constructor;
  · rintro ⟨ i, j, k, rfl ⟩;
    exact ⟨ i + j + k, by ring ⟩;
  · rintro ⟨ m, rfl ⟩;
    exact ⟨ m, 0, 0, by norm_num ⟩

/-
PROBLEM
An antichain subset of `{a^n}` has at most one element when `a ≥ 2`.

PROVIDED SOLUTION
By contraposition: if s.card ≥ 2, then by powers_not_antichain, s is not a division antichain.
-/
lemma antichain_of_powers_card_le_one {a : ℕ} (ha : 2 ≤ a) (s : Finset ℕ)
    (hsub : ∀ x ∈ s, ∃ n : ℕ, x = a ^ n)
    (hanti : IsDivisionAntichain s) : s.card ≤ 1 := by
  exact Classical.not_not.1 fun h => powers_not_antichain ha s hsub ( by linarith ) hanti

/-
PROBLEM
Key lemma: the sum of a singleton `{a^n}` is `a^n`.

PROVIDED SOLUTION
Finset.sum of a singleton {x} under id is just x. Use Finset.sum_singleton.
-/
lemma sum_singleton_power {a n : ℕ} : ({a ^ n} : Finset ℕ).sum id = a ^ n := by
  exact Finset.sum_singleton _ _

/-
PROBLEM
Not every sufficiently large natural is a power of `a` when `a ≥ 2`.

PROVIDED SOLUTION
Suppose for contradiction that eventually all n are powers of a. Then in particular there exists N such that for all n ≥ N, n is a power of a. But a^k and a^(k+1) differ by a^k*(a-1) ≥ 2 for large k. Specifically, consider n = a^k + 1 for sufficiently large k. If a^k + 1 = a^m for some m, then m > k (since a^k + 1 > a^k), so a^m ≥ a^(k+1), meaning a^k + 1 ≥ a*a^k, hence 1 ≥ (a-1)*a^k, which is impossible for a ≥ 2 and k ≥ 1. Actually simpler: show that a^k + 1 is not a power of a. Use Filter.Eventually.exists_gt or just exhibit a specific non-power. Actually the cleanest way: if all sufficiently large n are powers of a, then there are only finitely many non-powers below any bound, but the gaps between consecutive powers a^k grow without bound, contradicting that all sufficiently large n are powers.
-/
lemma not_eventually_power {a : ℕ} (ha : 2 ≤ a) :
    ¬ ∀ᶠ n : ℕ in atTop, ∃ m : ℕ, n = a ^ m := by
  -- For any natural number $n$, there exists a non-power of $a$ greater than $n$. We can construct such a number by taking $m = a^n + 1$.
  have h_non_power : ∀ n : ℕ, ∃ m : ℕ, n < m ∧ ¬∃ k : ℕ, m = a ^ k := by
    intro n
    use a ^ (n + 1) + 1;
    refine' ⟨ _, _ ⟩;
    · exact Nat.lt_succ_of_le ( Nat.le_of_lt ( Nat.recOn n ( by norm_num; linarith ) fun n ihn => by norm_num [ Nat.pow_succ ] at * ; nlinarith ) );
    · rintro ⟨ k, hk ⟩;
      have := congr_arg ( · % a ) hk ; norm_num [ Nat.add_mod, Nat.pow_mod, show a ≠ 0 by linarith ] at this;
      rcases k with ( _ | _ | k ) <;> rcases a with ( _ | _ | a ) <;> norm_num at *;
  contrapose! h_non_power;
  rw [ Filter.eventually_atTop ] at h_non_power; obtain ⟨ N, hN ⟩ := h_non_power; exact ⟨ N, fun m hm => by obtain ⟨ k, rfl ⟩ := hN _ hm.le; exact ⟨ k, rfl ⟩ ⟩ ;

/-
PROBLEM
**Counterexample**: `PowTripleSet a a a` is NOT d-complete for `a ≥ 2`.
This demonstrates that the pairwise coprimality condition in Erdős Problem 123
is necessary.

PROVIDED SOLUTION
Unfold IsDComplete and PowTripleSet. Suppose for contradiction it is d-complete. Then eventually every n has an antichain subset s of PowTripleSet a a a summing to n. By PowTripleSet_eq_self, every element of s is a power of a. By antichain_of_powers_card_le_one, s has at most 1 element. If s is empty, sum = 0. If s is a singleton {a^m}, sum = a^m. So eventually every n is either 0 or a power of a. But by not_eventually_power, not all sufficiently large n are powers of a. Contradiction.
-/
theorem not_d_complete_equal_base {a : ℕ} (ha : 2 ≤ a) :
    ¬ IsDComplete (PowTripleSet a a a) := by
  contrapose! ha with h;
  by_contra ha;
  -- Then eventually every n has an antichain subset s of PowTripleSet a a a summing to n.
  obtain ⟨N, hN⟩ : ∃ N, ∀ n ≥ N, ∃ s : Finset ℕ, (s : Set ℕ) ⊆ PowTripleSet a a a ∧ IsDivisionAntichain s ∧ s.sum id = n := by
    exact Filter.eventually_atTop.mp h;
  -- By `PowTripleSet_eq_self`, every element of s is a power of a.
  have h_powers : ∀ n ≥ N, ∃ m : ℕ, n = a ^ m ∨ n = 0 := by
    intros n hn
    obtain ⟨s, hs⟩ := hN n hn
    have hs_powers : ∀ x ∈ s, ∃ m : ℕ, x = a ^ m := by
      exact fun x hx => by rcases hs.1 hx with ⟨ i, j, k, rfl ⟩ ; exact ⟨ i + j + k, by ring ⟩ ;
    -- By `antichain_of_powers_card_le_one`, s has at most 1 element.
    have hs_card : s.card ≤ 1 := by
      exact antichain_of_powers_card_le_one ( by linarith ) s hs_powers hs.2.1;
    cases s using Finset.induction <;> aesop;
  -- This contradicts `not_eventually_power`, which states that not all sufficiently large n are powers of a.
  have h_contradiction : ∀ᶠ n : ℕ in atTop, ∃ m : ℕ, n = a ^ m := by
    filter_upwards [ Filter.eventually_ge_atTop N, Filter.eventually_gt_atTop 0 ] with n hn hn' using by obtain ⟨ m, rfl | rfl ⟩ := h_powers n hn <;> tauto;
  exact not_eventually_power ( by linarith ) h_contradiction

